plit up, and he's just making his way through life.<br><br>Then, one day, his wife throws out his last (and favorite) guitar.  This gets him all riled up, and a bit sentimental about the good old days.  Add to this a new babalicous co-worker who seems oddly interested in him, and he decides to go out and get stinking drunk.  In an odd twist of fate, the co-worker (Layla Yuuki, by name) finds him at the food cart where he's trying to find his lost youth at the bottom of a sake bottle.  There, she recognizes him as the lead rocker of Black Heaven, and they get drunk together.<br><br>While Oji's in a drunken stupor, Layla leads him off to a empty showroom model in a nearby housing project.  Instead of the hanky-panky you'd expect, Layla teleports them both to the flagship of an alien spacefleet.  (Whoa.  Did I loose anyone there?)  The crew of the ship shove his beloved guitar (which they saved from the trash heap) in his hands, and beg him to play.  He does, and it turns out that his music provides the missing waveform to activate the Ultimate Weapon(tm).  No, really.  I shit you not.  That's why there's the little motto &quot;Hard rock save the space!&quot; below the title.<br><br>Anyways, not to give things away, the rest of the series follows the odd combination of Oji rediscovering the rocker that lay buried beneath respectabilty for so long, as well as the space battles, which draw closer and closer to earth.  While he can blast the hell outta an entire alien fleet with his guitar, Oji has trouble reconciling his efforts to reform the band with his wife, who's No Fun anymore.  (Of course, she gets suspicious about him running off with Layla all the time, so that don't help much.)<br><br>Great animation, great music, a great story, and a lot of comic relief make this one helluva anime.  Rent it and see, or you will be destroyed!<br><br>Rating:  4 cheeses and 5 cookies, on a 0-5 cheese scale. <p>'He's cookin' in the kitchen of darkness - a big ol' pie of